AB  - Technical Abstract: Especially with the growing complexity of tampering methods like splicing and copy-move, image forgery detection is essential for digital forensics. This work suggests a dual-branch hybrid deep learning model combining the semantic abstraction capacity of EfficientNetB0 with the edge-aware, computationally efficient design of MobileNetV2. Using Global Average Pooling and dropout regularization for strong generalization, the design combines compound scaling with depthwise separable convolutions inside a unified framework. Feature vectors from both branches are combined to improve discriminative power across spatial and frequency domains. Demonstrating better performance in both identification and localization tasks, the model is trained and tested on five different benchmark datasets—Chinese Academy of Sciences Institute of Automation (CASIA V1), Columbia, DEFACTO-Splicing, DEFACTO-CopyMove, and Media Integration and Communication Center (MICC)-F2000. On the image and face manipulation detection and localization dataset (DEFACTO), it gets an Area Under Curve (AUC) of 1.00, F1-score of 0.99, and perfect recall (1.00); on MICC-F2000, it likewise provides 0.98 AUC and 0.98 F1-score. Consistent outperformance across 20＋state-of-the-art models in accuracy, robustness, and cross-dataset generalization is shown by comparative study. Non-Technical Abstract: Digital image manipulation is becoming more common, so areas like digital forensics and journalism need to make good tools for finding images that have been changed. The proposed work describes a simple, quick, and effective deep learning model that can find and label images that have been tampered with, like those that have been spliced or changed using copy-and-move methods. The model is made to use little computer power, which means it can be used in real time. It works well with a lot of different datasets and is especially good at finding small changes in photos, even if the changes are not very noticeable. The approach is exceptionally valuable for sectors where picture authenticity is essential, like security and media verification. Because it does not cost much to compute, it can be used in automated systems that check the authenticity of digital material. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd.
