TI  - From Past Innovations to Future Prospects: Advanced Computational Techniques in Automated Obscenity Detection
AU  - Rautela, Kamakshi
AU  - Vardhan, Harsh
AU  - Juneja, Akshay
AU  - Kumar, Vijay
T2  - Cybernetics and Systems
AB  - The expansion of digital media in recent years has created an immediate need for automated systems for reliable detection of obscene content. Such systems are essential for safeguarding users, upholding ethical standards, and ensuring compliance with regulatory frameworks. This paper surveys recent advances in deep learning methods, particularly convolutional neural networks (CNNs), recurrent neural networks (RNNs), and emerging transformer-based and vision–language models. We emphasize how these approaches are integrated within engineering frameworks, ranging from distributed cloud pipelines to edge deployments, to support large-scale content moderation. The reviewed methods demonstrate strong capabilities in learning complex visual and contextual patterns, leading to high performance in tasks such as obscene image and video classification. Computational strategies that improve accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, AUC, and real-time latency are highlighted, along with challenges of scalability, dataset bias, adversarial attacks, and resource constraints. By combining technical insights with discussions of ethical and privacy considerations, this review proposes a multidisciplinary framework for building more precise, fair, and resilient obscenity detection systems. The work serves as a practical reference for engineers, developers, and policymakers while outlining open challenges and future opportunities, including multimodal moderation, deepfake detection, and privacy-preserving learning approaches. © 2026 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.
