TI  - Dual-Filter Based Deepfake Detection Using CNN and Vision Transformer
AU  - Ali, Aashna
AU  - M, Ankitha
AU  - Vanamala, H R
AB  - This study introduces a novel deepfake detection framework that leverages Laplacian and Hessian image filters as a dual-channel input, shifting the focus from raw RGB pixels to structural and texture-level inconsistencies often hidden to the human eye. By emphasizing edges and fine-grained anomalies, the approach enhances the interpretability of learned features while reducing reliance on superficial color patterns. Two architectures are explored: a custom Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), which captures localized edge irregularities, and a Vision Transformer (ViT), adapted to process filtered dual-channel representations through its attention-driven mechanism. Both models were trained and tested under identical conditions, ensuring a fair evaluation. The CNN achieved a strong accuracy of approximately 77%, though it struggled in cases of subtle manipulations, while the ViT delivered superior performance with nearly 80% accuracy, showing greater resilience against ambiguous forgeries. By combining explainable filter-based preprocessing with advanced transformer-based learning, this study offers a pathway toward detection methods that remain robust even as manipulation techniques continue to evolve.
