TI  - Securing Reality: AI-Driven Detection of Deepfakes and Counterfeit Currency
AU  - Jambula, Nithin
AU  - Reddy, Nalla Krishna
AU  - Pandey, Kshama
AU  - M, Mahesh
AB  - The rapid growth of AI-generated media and high-resolution printing has intensified the dual threats of deepfake content and counterfeit currency, eroding public trust and financial security. This paper presents two complementary detection frameworks. For deepfakes, a spatial-temporal CNN-LSTM pipeline captures frame-level artifacts and sequence dynamics, enabling robust video analysis. For counterfeit currency, a multi-stage rule-based system combines HSV-based segmentation, geometric validation, and feature-wise scoring of security elements (e.g., Gandhi portrait, watermark, micro-lettering, and security thread). Evaluated on real and synthetic video/image datasets, the CNN-LSTM model attains a validation accuracy of 91.25 %, while the currency system correctly flags 95 % of forged notes (19/20), highlighting resilience to high-quality reproductions. Both frameworks are designed for real-time operation and emphasize explainability through structured outputs and feature-level confidence reporting. The results demonstrate that integrating deep learning with rule-based verification delivers scalable, transparent, and accurate defenses against modern media and financial forgeries, offering a practical foundation for deployment in security-critical workflows.
