AU  - Neogi, Suman Kumar
AU  - Jaiswal, Niraj
AU  - Ghosh, Papri
AU  - Das, Subhram
AU  - Mondal, Md. Ashifuddin
AB  - The rapid advancement of deepfake technology, driven by AI and deep learning, has revolutionized media creation but poses significant threats to privacy, cybersecurity, and public trust. This study explores Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) as a primary approach for deepfake detection, integrating hybrid frameworks with transformer-based models. The proposed methodology employs a multi-attentional CNN framework alongside a Conditional Encoder-Decoder GAN (CED-DCGAN) to analyze spatial and temporal inconsistencies in manipulated media. Extensive experiments were conducted on benchmark datasets such as FaceForensics++, CelebA-HQ, and the DeepFake Detection Challenge (DFDC) to evaluate detection efficacy. The results demonstrate that the hybrid model achieves a remarkable accuracy of 98.23%, surpassing traditional CNN-based and semi-supervised GAN models. Additionally, adversarial training enhances robustness against attack scenarios, maintaining 89.7% accuracy. Despite challenges in computational efficiency, the findings contribute to the development of scalable deepfake detection systems, reinforcing digital media integrity and trust. The future research should focus on optimizing real-time applicability and enhancing explainability for practical deployment.
