TI  - Hybrid DeepFake Detection Using Xception and XGBoost with Bayesian Optimization
AU  - Pacaldo, Paolo L.
AU  - Matias, Junrie B.
AU  - Jayoma, Jaymer M.
AU  - Abalorio, Cristopher C.
AU  - Gonzales, Clark Justine
AU  - Dalaorao, Gleen A.
AB  - Deepfakes pose a significant challenge to media integrity by generating highly realistic manipulated videos that are difficult to detect with conventional methods. This study proposes a hybrid deepfake detection framework that integrates spatial feature extraction from video frames using a pre-trained Xception convolutional neural network and classification via an XGBoost model fine-tuned through Bayesian Optimization. The approach employs a memory-efficient streamed pipeline to process keyframes from the DeepFake Detection (DFD) dataset, achieving 92.5% accuracy, perfect recall for fake videos, and competitive performance against state-of-the-art baselines including MesoNet, EfficientNet-B7, and Vision Transformer. Comparative experiments and an ablation study demonstrate the benefits of combining deep CNN-based feature extraction with optimized gradient boosting for real-time, scalable, and interpretable deepfake detection. This work highlights the potential of hybrid architectures to address the growing challenge of manipulated media in security-critical contexts.
