AU  - Madhavi, Juturu Bindu
AU  - Thanuja, Mandlukose
AU  - Jagadish, Dyvamdinne
AU  - Depuru, SivaKumar
AB  - The rapid advancement of deepfake generation techniques has posed a huge challenge to the security of digital communication and above all, the messaging apps where the content can be manipulated and distributed in a split second. Existing detection methods, which mostly rely on Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), have a set of limitations to their adaptability, computational efficiency, and resistance against the evolving forgery methods. This paper suggests a Lightweight Vision Transformer (L-ViT) that would be a streamlined solution dedicated to the deepfake detection task in constrained resource solutions. The model uses adaptive multi-scale receptive fields with self-attention to identify local and global discrepancies in manipulated media at relatively no parameter reduction and low computational complexity. The L-ViT is trained on augmented datasets and with transfer learning, boasts better results than CNN baselines as well as similar accuracy compared to full-scale Vision Transformers with an accuracy of 94.1% and 0.97 AUC-ROC on benchmark datasets. Tests of robustness against benign transformations which include resizing, compression and noise verify the robustness of the model with slight performances. The identified approach is accurate, flexible, and effectively finds the right balance that enables edge devices to detect deepfake threats in real-time communication networks.
