AU  - Movaliya, Meet
AU  - T, Padmavathy
AB  - In this research, a novel technique to differentiate face swap deepfakes in videos is proposed using the Hybrid CNN-SNN model, referred to as “A Hybrid SNN model for Face-Swap Deepfake Detection”. The objective is to improve spatial and temporal detection of face-swapped manipulations using a dual neural architecture. Spatial feature extraction is performed by the CNN (Convolutional Neural Network) component, leveraging variability in facial texture, light, and expression. Temporal analysis is executed by the SNN (Spiking Neural Network) component, identifying abnormalities such as unnatural blinking patterns and head movements. The model was trained on the Face Forensics++ dataset consisting of 1000 labeled samples for both real and fake data. With a training loss of 0.3 and validation loss of 0.6, the model achieved training accuracy of 90% and validation accuracy of 80%, demonstrating promising results. These results indicate strong performance, particularly in capturing subtle temporal artifacts. However, they also highlight limitations such as high computational cost, limited generalizability to newer deepfake techniques, and challenges in real-time deployment on edge devices. The proposed method shows potential for forensic and security applications, especially in low-resource environments where SNNs perform well with temporal data since they inherent energy efficiency and low-latency temporal processing to the approach. Future work will focus on enhancing model robustness and generalization by diversifying datasets and optimizing for deployment on robotics and IoT.
