TY  - CONF
TI  - Deepfake Detection: Bi-LSTM Framework with MobileNetV2
AU  - V, Premanand
AU  - S, Akil
AU  - S, Aniruth Narayanan
AB  - The combination of state-of-the-art deep learning technology which produces deepfakes causes major trust issues that affect people's ability to believe in digital materials. Most established detection methods analyze complete video frames even though they contain considerable useless background information. Such detection techniques perform worse while using more computational resources which makes them unpractical for real-time processing under resource-limited conditions. The proposed framework operates in real-time to detect deepfake changes specifically in facial areas because this is where the most likely fake modifications take place. The first step of the model uses Haar Cascade Classifiers to detect faces and separate them from the video frames. The facial regions undergo processing via MobileNetV2 to accomplish spatial feature extraction. A Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (Bi-LSTM) network serves as part of the model to detect temporal inconsistencies found between video sequences because they act as synthetic content indicators. The model uses an attention mechanism to improve understanding and channel its analysis toward essential temporal video segments. The system assessment on Celeb-DF (v2) yielded 95.55 % accuracy along with 89 % F1-score, 82 % precision and 97 % recall. The system demonstrates high efficiency for differentiating between genuine and fake video footage. The model demonstrates optimized performance with minimal processing requirements which enables its real-time use in digital forensic probes as well as media authentication checks and safeguarding applications during security operations. This study suggests an efficient approach to counter the dangeroud deepfake threats through the combination of facial area extraction and deep learning spatial interpretation and sequence-level time research. The proposed system delivers high precision in detection and maintains sufficient lightness to work effectively in mobile and edge computational platforms.
