AU  - Kalpana
AU  - Singh, Kaushik
AU  - Kumar, Krish
AU  - Prajapati, Yogendra Narayan
AU  - Mishra, Kriti
AB  - The rapid advancement of deepfake technologies poses significant threats to digital security, misinformation mitigation, and privacy preservation. Existing detection methods often struggle with generalization across diverse datasets and manipulation techniques. This paper proposes a hybrid deepfake detection framework that integrates EfficientNetB4, attention mechanisms, and Vision Transformers (ViTs) to enhance detection accuracy and robustness. For preprocessing, the proposed framework employs Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) and Local Binary Patterns (LBP) to derive distinctive features capturing both spatial and frequency domain information. EfficientNetB4 serves as the backbone for efficient hierarchical feature extraction, while attention mechanisms localize suspicious regions and ViTs model global contextual relationships. An ensemble strategy consolidates predictions across components. Evaluations on FaceForensics++, DFDC, and COCOFake datasets demonstrate superior performance, achieving 92.4% accuracy, 0.912 F1-score, and 0.751 AUC on FaceForensics++. Comparative analysis shows improvements over XceptionNet (89.3% vs. 92.4% accuracy) and MesoNet (85.1% vs. 92.4%). Ablation studies confirm critical contributions from FFT (89.1 % \rightarrow 92.4 % accuracy) and attention mechanisms (88.3 % \rightarrow 92.4 %). The framework exhibits cross-dataset generalization with 89.7% accuracy on DFDC and 87.4% on COCOFake. This work advances robust deepfake detection through synergistic integration of convolutional networks, attention, and transformer architectures, providing an effective solution against evolving synthetic media threats.
