TI  - Audio Deepfakes Detection: A Comprehensive Literature Review of Voice Cloning Fraud Detection Techniques
AU  - Chauhan, Shivani
AU  - Sethi, Kapil
AU  - Anand, Abhineet
AB  - Audio deepfakes are synthetic speech generated by next-generation TTS and voice-conversion approaches are enabling large-scale fraud and impersonation. This review provides an overview of detection techniques, ranging from hand-crafted spectral and prosodic cues to deep learning and self-supervised methods, all evaluated on standardized datasets such as ASVspoof and ADD. Hybrid models that leverage spectrograms, pitch, and attention form a particularly high-performing group, but the need to generalize detection across labeled datasets and withstand adversarial attacks remains unresolved. Restrictions on horsepower, privacy, and interpretability remain limiting factors for real-time deployment. Detecting deepfakes in lower-resource languages and realistic extra-linguistic conditions remains an open area of work. Moving forward, the audio-visual modality of truth and trust, the need for explainable frameworks for detection, and standards closely resembling human 'speech-perception-like' measures are crucial. We must improve traditional technical detection and bolster human detection capabilities at the same time. This review also offers a survey of the field and highlights important areas where further research needs to be pushed forward next.
