AU  - D, Aditya Singh
AU  - Patel, Pratik
AU  - Patel, Warish
AB  - The spread of deepfakes - synthetically generated media created using generative adversarial networks (GANs) - represents growing risks to digital trust, security and public debate. Here, they survey the emerging frontier of real-time deepfake detection, highlighting convolutional neural network (CNN) and generative adversarial network (GAN) fingerprinting methods. While CNNs are great at learning spatial and temporal patterns that are indicative of synthetic media, new GAN fingerprinting techniques are being developed to track unique generative signatures that are embedded in forgeries. Together, these methods make up a two-layered protect against sophisticated forgery. We discuss recent advances, benchmark datasets, real-time deployment issues, and the combination of model interpretability with detection speed. Special focus is given to the interplay between adversarial robustness and computational efficiency in real-time systems. By bringing together current methodologies and future directions, this survey will serve as a comprehensive starting point for researchers and practitioners, helping them stay ahead in the ongoing escalating arms race against deepfake generation.
