TI  - Attention-Guided Spatial Temporal Framework for Deepfake Detection on Social Video Platforms
AU  - Ashokkumar, Saranya
AU  - Amistapuram, Keerthi
AU  - C, Bharathi.
AU  - M, Dhanamalar.
AU  - J, Gokulraj.
AB  - In the past several years, deepfake videos have emerged as a substantial threat to the authenticity of information posted on social video platforms, as deepfake videos are increasingly realistic and accessible. Deepfake detection requires analyzing both spatial artifacts/signal characteristics at the individual frame level and temporal inconsistencies between frames within the video. In this manuscript, a hybrid framework which Attention-based Spatial-Temporal Representation for Identifying Deepfakes (ASTRID) is proposed. Each video clip is first preprocessed using a Multi-task Cascaded Convolutional Network (MTCNN) based pipeline to perform accurate face detection and alignment, followed by uniform frame extraction and normalization. Each frame is then input into a Unified Attention Maps based Network (UAM-Net) backbone, which consist of an EfficientNet-B4 encoder, to extract discriminative spatial features through spatial and channel attention mechanisms, effectively identifying manipulated spatial regions. The extracted sequence of frame-level embeddings is then input into a lightweight Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) with temporal attention to model dependencies between frames and motion anomalies that characterize deepfake modifications. Finally, the video-level representation is input into a fully connected layer with sigmoid activation for better binary classification.
