TI  - Detection of Deepfake Videos Created Through Face Swapping Techniques
AU  - S, Shruthi.
AU  - R, Manjunath
AB  - The increasing prevalence of deepfake technology particularly its ability to alter facial identities in videos and images using artificial intelligence—has raised serious concerns about the reliability of visual content, especially in journalism and media reporting. This project aims to build an advanced deep learning system capable of detecting face-based deepfake manipulations specifically for use in news forensics. The proposed solution leverages Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) to analyse facial patterns and identify irregularities indicative of tampered or synthetically generated content. Using datasets such as FaceForensics++, the model will be trained to recognize both authentic and manipulated videos, with a focus on overcoming challenges such as video compression and adversarial inputs that often escape detection by traditional methods. Ethical concerns, including user privacy and responsible implementation, will be addressed to ensure the technology is used in a socially responsible manner. Furthermore, the system will incorporate advanced preprocessing techniques, data augmentation strategies, and adversarial training to improve robustness and generalization. In addition to enhancing detection performance, the project also aims to raise awareness about the dangers of deepfake technology in the news industry and support efforts to safeguard digital media integrity.
