TY  - CONF
TI  - Lightweight Deepfake Detection for Real-World Augmented Images in Social Media
AU  - Kashyap, Aryan
AU  - Mehak
AU  - Sarkar, Sobhan
AU  - Pramanik, Anima
AB  - Deepfake detection continues to face significant challenges when dealing with unfamiliar identities, emerging manipulation techniques, and degraded visual quality, which become even more critical in real-world scenarios such as social media, where images and videos are frequently compressed and distorted by noise. Existing methods rely heavily on large labeled datasets but still struggle to generalize effectively across unseen domains. To address this, we propose a lightweight deepfake detection framework specifically designed for augmented images common on social media and optimized for real-time use on edge devices. Our approach integrates global facial representations with localized texture cues through a dual-stream network model, enabling robustness under distortions while maintaining low computational overhead. We systematically evaluate the framework under varying levels of augmentation, including compression, noise, and blurring, and benchmark it against state-of-the-art detectors. Results demonstrate that our model achieves competitive accuracy with significantly reduced complexity, while GradCAM visualizations across different augmentation conditions provide interpretability by revealing how distortions affect the model's attention toward manipulated regions, thereby offering actionable insights for improving robustness.
