TY  - CONF
TI  - A Survey on Deepfake Detection Techniques for Watermarking and Digital Forensics Using Deep Learning
AU  - S, Suhasini T
AU  - Sharma, Manisha
AU  - Mishra, Deviprasad
AB  - The rapid development of deepfake technology has introduced new challenges to content authenticity, especially in legal and forensic domains where the integrity of digital media is paramount. Deep fakes have further complicated watermarking efforts, making it difficult to assert media ownership or validate tamper resistance. This survey aims to examine and categorize existing deepfake detection techniques from a deep learning perspective, with an emphasis on their integration into digital watermarking and forensic applications. A comprehensive literature review is conducted to explore deep learning-based detection methods such as CNNs, RNNs, attention mechanisms, and facial geometry models. The study also investigates how these techniques can support robust watermarking strategies and forensic traceability. The review reveals that hybrid architectures such as ResNet-Swish-BiLSTM and spatiotemporal attention networks achieve high accuracy in detecting manipulated media. Additionally, deep learning is shown to enhance the effectiveness of watermarking and forensic workflows by enabling tamper detection, content attribution, and source verification. Deep learning-driven deepfake detection offers promising solutions not only for real-time content authentication but also for long-term forensic verification and digital watermarking. Future work should focus on building integrated frameworks that combine detection, provenance tracking, and legal admissibility.
