TI  - Empirical Research on Facial Deepfake Detection: Taxonomy, Challenges, and Future Directions
AU  - Supriya Kulkarni, P
AU  - Pradeep Kumar, N S
AB  - The rapid development of generative models has led to the rise of deepfakes which are incredibly realistic manipulated media that pose serious dangers to security, privacy, and public trust. This survey specifically demonstrates a detailed assessment of the existing deep fake detection methods that includes neural networks, residual networks, attention methods, transformer algorithms and hybrid methods. Each method is computed based on their strengths, weaknesses, dataset and performance of the benchmark evaluations. Further, the comparative analysis comprises the trade-off between different methods with respect to accuracy, interpretability, computational efficiency and scalability. Thus, the evaluation signifies the existing challenges of generalizability to unseen manipulations and robustness under various conditions such as compression, noise and low-resolution media. Finally, the survey identifies gaps in research, absence of scalable and efficient systems suitable for real-time applications. Then, based on the observed gaps in current approaches and research evidence, the future directions for the deepfake detection systems determines that lightweight hybrid transformer-based approaches that integrate spatial, temporal, and frequency-domain characteristics are required to improve the accuracy, efficiency, and robustness through flexibility for practical deployment in diverse and dynamic deployments.
