TY  - CONF
TI  - Implementation of Machine Learning Techniques for Real-Time Deep Fake Voice Detection
AU  - Singh, Kaushal
AU  - Sanghani, Parag
AU  - Shah, Niraj
AB  - Growing numbers of audio material made by computers, also called "deep fake voices," are very dangerous to people's privacy, the security of information, and computers. Aiming to correctly identify fake voice changes, this study demonstrates and analyzes real-time machine learning (ML) methods. Specifically, a special dataset with 15,000 audio clips (50 percent real and 50 percent fake) was created and used for testing. Multiple machine learning models could be fully analyzed using features like Mel Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCC), pitch, and spectral difference that were extracted. Random Forest (91.7%) and Support Vector Machine (SVM) algorithms were beaten by Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN), which got 96.2% accuracy. Based on real-time application tests, CNN recognition delay was an average of 0.45 seconds per 5-second audio section, proving that it is suitable for use in real-world situations. CNN clearly did better than the other models that were tried, as shown by its positive Area Under Curve (AUC) score of 0.97 in a Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) analysis. With precision and memory rates of 95.4% and 94.8%, respectively, CNN's better performance and stability are further demonstrated. When compared to high recognition rates, the model had a 3.8% false-positive rate, showing that it needs to be improved. Results show that CNN-based machine learning models can be useful for fighting deep fake audio risks, which could lead to better real-time security solutions. For better precision and fewer false findings, it is suggested that future study combine multi-modal data analysis with advanced signal processing methods.
