TI  - Interpretable Deepfake Detection: Enhancing Real vs. Fake Face Classification with Explainable AI and Transfer Learning
AU  - P, Abinash.
AU  - Krishnamoorthy, N.
AU  - Vinothkumar, V.
AB  - Deepfake detection is a vital challenge in the age of cognitive computing because of its security, misinformation, and identity fraud implications. Article presents an interpretable deepfake detection model built on the DenseNet121 architecture to categorize real and fake faces. The model is trained on a 140,000 images dataset with data augmentation and transfer learning method. Optimized training methods-e.g., early stopping, adaptive learning rate planning, and checkpointing-guarantee effective convergence and overfitting prevention. For added transparency, several Explainable AI (XAI) methods, namely Integrated Gradients, Grad-CAM, Occlusion Sensitivity, Vanilla Gradients, and LIME, are combined to visualize and explain model decisions. These explainability tools demonstrate the network's attention to semantically useful facial areas, building model trustworthiness and diagnostic understanding. Experimental outcomes reveal a 98% classification accuracy, which surpasses baseline models and verifies the reliability of the proposed approach. This article contributes to the development of explainable, high-accuracy AI systems for deepfake detection, which supports the significance of interpretability in security-critical applications
