TI  - Deepfake Detection Using Live Facial Analysis for Secure Folder Access via Web Interface
AU  - Hemalatha, S.
AU  - Sivasundaram, Malatthi
AU  - P, Nithya
AU  - K, Kalaivendhan
AU  - K, Jestin M
AU  - T, Giri
AB  - This study presents a web-based secure access system that employs real-time facial analysis combined with deepfake detection to control access to private folders. The proposed framework leverages a hybrid deep learning model that integrates Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) for extracting spatial facial features with Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks, supported by Multi-task Cascaded Convolutional Networks (MTCNN), for capturing temporal consistency and detecting subtle artifacts indicative of synthetic media. This dual-architecture approach enables the system to effectively distinguish between genuine live facial inputs and deepfake forgeries in real time. A comprehensive dataset containing both real and synthetically generated facial sequences was utilized for model training and evaluation. Experimental results demonstrate that the hybrid CNN-LSTM/MTCNN model achieved an accuracy of 94.2%, significantly surpassing traditional CNN-only approaches, which attained 89% accuracy. Statistical analysis using an Independent Samples t-test confirmed the improvement's significance, with a p-value < 0.000, indicating strong reliability of the performance gain. The system's design allows seamless integration into a browser-based interface, enabling immediate access decision-making without manual verification. This approach enhances biometric authentication security by mitigating spoofing attempts, including advanced AI-driven facial forgeries. Consequently, the proposed method offers robust protection against identity theft, presenting a scalable and practical solution for secure folder access in sensitive digital environments.
