TI  - Comparative Analysis of Deep Learning Architectures for Robust Deepfake Detection using Transfer Learning
AU  - C, Thilagavathi
AU  - S, Harshivpranav R
AU  - C, Kishor
AU  - S, Muthuprakash
AU  - G, Vasanth
AB  - The technology of deepfakes poses significant threats to the digital security, the authenticity of media and population trust by creating very believable manipulated facial images and videos. With the advancement of the generative models, the existing detection techniques have been less useful, and they require robust and generalizable solutions. The paper provides a comparative study of the most notable deep learning models such as VGG19, ResNet50, XceptionNet and EfficientNet using transfer learning to successfully detect deepfakes. On a benchmark dataset (e.g. FaceForensics++ and Celeb-DF) a fine-tuning of each model is conducted using pre-trained ImageNet weights and subjected to multiple manipulation conditions. Detailed performance evaluations based on accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score and AUC metrics indicate that XceptionNet has better performance compared to the other models because it has depthwise separable convolutions and EfficientNet has a good balance between detection accuracy and efficiency. The analysis highlights the unique merits and shortcomings of each architecture and gives important observations towards the design of next generation scalable and real-time multimedia forensic systems.
