AU  - Rabbi Ahmed, Khandakar
AU  - Robin, Shahriar Alam
AU  - Nesar, Shah Tawkir
AU  - Salam, Towfika
AU  - Ahsan, Md. Naimul
AU  - Ansari, Md Eahia
AB  - The artificially created media produced with the aid of artificial intelligence (AI), commonly referred to as deepfakes, are posing a serious challenge to the integrity of Management Information Systems (MIS). To achieve this, the paper proposes a new deep learning (DL) model, DGAF-Net (DenseNet + Gabor Attention Fusion Network), to enhance the accuracy of detecting such manipulated content. DGAF-Net incorporates DenseNet121, which is used to extract semantic features with the Gabor filter as a texture feature to generate this information through a Gated Attention Fusion Mechanism (GAFM). The pair of branches in this organization enables the successful detection of both local and global facial image anomalies, particularly in realistic scenarios with compression and noise. When tested on the FaceForensics++ dataset, the model attains a better accuracy of 88.33%, which is better than current baselines, such as Vision Transformer (ViT-B16) and Swin Transformer + CNN fusion models. The findings demonstrate the validity, scalability, efficiency, and generality of DGAF-Net as a solution for real-time MIS digital forensics, as well as a scalable approach to deepfake methods that are becoming increasingly advanced.
