TI  - A Multimodal Deep Fake Detection Framework for Robust and Efficient Synthetic Media Identification
AU  - Duraimurugan, N
AU  - Kumar, P
AU  - Jayaprakash, R
AB  - The fast pace of deep fake technology poses digital integrity risks by facilitating hyper-realistic synthetic media, resulting in misinformation, identity theft, and security violations. Current detection systems lack robustness, generalization, and real-time efficiency and frequently fail against adversarial attacks. This paper presents a multimodal deep fake detection framework that combines spatial, temporal, and sequential analysis through cutting-edge deep learning methods. The model utilizes adaptive preprocessing, multi-scale feature representation, and temporal self-attention mechanisms to improve detection accuracy and robustness. Hybrid architecture integrating EfficientNetV2, a lightweight 3D CNN, and Bi-LSTM with Transformer layers provides better anomaly detection along with computational efficiency. The proposed approach provides improved accuracy in detecting subtle deep fake artifacts, better robustness against changing forgery attacks, and optimized efficiency for realworld applications. Experimental results prove to be better than current alternatives, further enhancing trust in digital content and boosting defences against synthetic media threats.
