TI  - Hybrid Swin Transformer–EfficientNetV2 Model for Robust and Explainable Deepfake Detection
AU  - P, Yuvarani
AU  - T, Maragatham
AU  - S, Gokul Kanna
AB  - Deepfake content poses a significant threat to the authenticity, privacy, and cybersecurity of digital multimedia, for which the literature has been seeking efficient detection frameworks with high accuracy, robustness, and scalability. Both classic CNNs and state-of-the-art transformer-based models demonstrate effectiveness for these tasks; however, CNNs suffer from a lack of generalization to unseen forgery types, while more recent transformers are hindered by their computational complexity. In this paper, we propose a hybrid framework that combines the Swin Transformer's shifted-window self-attention with optimized convolutional blocks from EfficientNetV2 to capture both hierarchical global dependencies and fine-grained local textures. By combining the preprocessing components that are augmented and scaled in a balanced manner, and by engineering temporal and contextual features such as blink deviation, motion consistency, lip-synchronization failures, and illumination quality issues, its robustness is further enhanced. Experiments on the Celeb-DF and DFDC benchmark datasets showed a detection accuracy of 94.3%, precision of 95.1%, recall of 93.8%, and F1-score of 94.4%, surpassing existing state-of-the-art baselines, including Xception and CapsuleNet. Moreover, adversarial robustness testing revealed no more than 3% accuracy degradation when under attack on the perturbed inputs, and the model achieved 22 frames per second on an RTX-class GPU, demonstrating near real-time capability. Grad-CAM and SHAP provide explainability, making the forensic process more transparent. Such a hybrid model, which constitutes an interpretable, scalable, and robust deepfake detection system, has the potential to be applied in various domains, including cybersecurity, digital forensics, and social media content validation.
