AU  - Wanjale, Kirti
AU  - Kelkar, Advait B.
AU  - Kendre, Yeshwant N.
AB  - Misleading digital content including deepfake videos, machine-generated audio and fake news reports has become highly prevalent in the creation and dissemination of content with the advent of generative artificial intelligence. These advances pose very significant threats on the credibility of information and the trust to the society in general. Unluckily, the current practice of fact-checking is fragile both in terms of speedy response and the ability to handle such problems at a large scale. The current paper is the suggestion of an artificial intelligence-based real-time system of deepfakes and misinformation detection and classification to a wide variety of media types, including text, images, and audio. The method is based on the techniques of Natural Language Processing, Computer Vision, and Audio Signal Processing to identify the tampered material, evaluate the emotional tone, and define the relevance of the information. The system proposed is a combination of modular components to offer end-to-end analysis and real-time feedback. It is believed that this piece will enhance digital safety, add value to fact-checkers and journalists, and make citizens aware about the responsible use of artificial intelligence.
