TI  - Using Machine Learning to Detect Deepfake Videos on Social Sites
AU  - Kavitha, T.
AU  - Hemalatha, S.
AU  - Ajaykanna, K.
AU  - Dinesh, S.
AU  - A.Jabastin
AB  - The use of machine-learning-based method to detect deepfake videos on social media platforms stems from the problem of increasing deepfake videos being posted on social media while concerns over misinformation, reputational damage, privacy violations, and online scams are proliferating. This work proposes new method for using machine learning to find deepfake videos, leveraging key-frame extraction in video analysis and using a recent deep learning approach, CNN and LSTM hybrid. Our approach begins with the extraction of salient frames from video for analysis, thus minimizing computational burden while retaining visual information that is salient to the identification task. The CNN discovers spatial features within frames, finding features that represent artifacts of manipulation. The LSTM analyzes video by accounting for the temporal dimension across frames examining commonalities and inconsistencies in sequences of frames and video, building specificity of the detection approach. In experimental assessment, our hybrid CNN-LSTM model outperformed the conventional approach in distinguishing between authentic and deepfaked videos using benchmark datasets. The results of the experiment suggest that spatial and temporal analysis can effectively identify deepfakes resulting in detection platform that will scale to applications on social media.
