TI  - Detecting Deepfakes using ConvNeXt and TimeSformer
AU  - T M, Rajesh
AU  - Dhangi, Shravankumar
AB  - Deepfakes, synthetic media generated using deep learning, pose serious threats to privacy, security, and public trust. Hence, suitable detection methods are required to combat them. This project aims to tackle the limitations of current methods by presenting a deep learning-based approach to detect deepfakes. Leveraging transfer learning, a pre-trained ConvNext model performs feature extraction to discern subtle, spatial artifacts within individual frames. In parallel, a TimeSformer model is employed to analyze video clips, enabling the detection of temporal inconsistencies and motion artifacts that single-frame methods miss. To provide a conclusive video verdict, clip-level predictions are aggregated, while Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM) and LIME (Local Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations) visualizations are used to visualize the model's decision process for transparency. We enhance generalization by training on diverse datasets and fine-tuning with augmented examples. Moreover, MediaPipe framework is used for high-speed face extraction to reduce the prediction time for real-time applications. This solution contributes to the development of powerful systems for detecting manipulated media.
