TI  - Optimizing the Biometric Authentication Scheme to Detect the Deepfake in Real Time Using GAN
AU  - Dash, Manoranjan
AU  - Reddy, A Mallikarjuna
AU  - Pulapa, Deekshitha
AU  - Kodakandla, Varshini
AU  - Gavini, Kavya
AB  - In today's technology, the impact of deepfake in society is huge and major cause of security concern. So many people have been affected with mental disorder as well as social reputation. Further, few people make suicide without informing the same to cybercrime personals. The proliferation of deepfake technologies poses significant threats to digital authenticity. Several systems use machine learning and deep learning to combat deepfakes, including CNNs for spatial analysis and RNNs or LSTMs for temporal inconsistencies. Methods like audio-visual mismatches, forensic pixel analysis, and pre-trained models such as XceptionNet and Capsule Networks show promise but face challenges like slow processing, limited dataset diversity, and susceptibility to adversarial attacks. This work introduces an advanced system optimized to identify deepfake manipulations by utilizing Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs). The model is designed to strengthen biometric authentication by distinguishing genuine and fake identities through enhanced image and video analysis techniques. By leveraging the adversarial architecture of GANs, the system learns to detect subtle anomalies that indicate deepfake artifacts. The solution integrates seamlessly into existing security frameworks, providing real-time processing and a user-friendly interface for immediate verification. Extensive testing and feedback will refine the system's accuracy and robustness. The ultimate goal is to ensure secure and reliable authentication systems that can effectively mitigate deepfake-related threats, validated through metrics like detection rate, processing speed, and resilience to adversarial attacks.
