TI  - Optimization of Forged Face Detection via Attention-based Bi-directional Long Short-Term Memory Networks
AU  - Wang, Tingting
AB  - With the rapid development of DeepFake and other face forgery generation methods, the authenticity of digital media has been severely undermined.Conventional detection approaches that rely solely on static frame-by-frame analysis often fail to capture temporal inconsistencies between adjacent frames. This study aims to develop a real-time, application-oriented deepfake picture detection method based on an attention-enhanced bidirectional long short-term memory network (Bi-LSTMAttention). The proposed method is designed to overcome the limitations of existing techniques in both efficiency and accuracy. The experimental dataset consists of \mathbf6 0, 0 0 0 facial images, with 30,000 real faces sourced from Celeb-DF and FaceForensics++ datasets, and 30,000 forged faces generated using Midjourney and DeepFake-TIMIT. The results demonstrate that the he proposed attention-based Bi-LSTM method demonstrates superior performance in real-time detection. Compared with BP neural networks, single LSTM, bidirectional LSTM models, Transformer-based models, and EfficientNet, it achieves notable improvements, yielding a Precision of 91.2 %, a Recall of 88.3 %, and a mean Average Precision (mAP) of 93.1 %.
