TY  - CONF
TI  - Secure and Efficient AI Architectures for Real-Time Video Forensics
AU  - Badawy, Wael
AB  - Real-time video manipulation detection and content authentication have emerged as critical challenges in the era of AI-generated media. The proliferation of deepfakes, adversarial attacks, and synthetic video content threatens information integrity and digital trust. In this paper, we propose VIDSEC-Net, a novel hybrid AI framework that integrates transformer-based vision encoders, adversarially trained classifiers, and spatiotemporal consistency models to detect manipulations in compressed, streamed, and archived video data. Unlike existing solutions, VIDSEC-Net is optimized for edge deployment and supports zero-trust environments through embedded cryptographic watermark validation and federated update mechanisms. We begin by formulating the mathematical problem of video tampering as a dynamic multivariate anomaly detection task across temporal frames and motion vectors. Our architecture leverages hierarchical attention across frame sequences, coupled with frequency-domain residual analysis, enabling high-precision detection even under post-processing or compression. The system is validated on multiple benchmark datasets (FaceForensics++, DeepfakeTIMIT, DFDC, and YouTube-Forensics) and demonstrates state-of-the-art performance in accuracy, F1-score, and adversarial robustness. In addition to performance metrics, we analyze VID-SEC-Net's real-time throughput on edge platforms (NVIDIA Jetson, Apple M1, Intel Movidius) and benchmark against transformer-lite and CNN baselines. Ethical implications, including potential misuse and dataset bias, are discussed, and we propose a set of deployment guidelines for privacy-preserving and trustworthy media verification. Our contributions offer a secure, scalable, and explainable AI-based solution for video forensics, setting the foundation for future research in trustaware media processing.
