TI  - AI Generated Audio Detection Using Acoustic Audio Features
AU  - Fathima Nuska, Mohamed Fayik
AU  - Firdhous, Mohamed Fazil Mohamed
AB  - The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence in text-to-speech technologies has led to highly realistic AI generated voices, raising concerns about audio deepfakes and their potential misuse in misinformation and identity fraud. This study presents a deep learning-based approach for detecting AI-generated audio by analyzing key acoustic features. A balanced dataset was collected using human speech from the CREMA-D dataset and AI generated audio from advanced TTS systems. Features such as 12 Mel Frequency Cepstral Coefficients, pitch, zero- crossing rate, spectral centroid, and spectral bandwidth were extracted. A Convolutional Neural Network was trained on these features, achieving 98% accuracy in distinguishing human from AI-generated audio. The model captures subtle differences in tone, pitch, and frequency patterns, offering a scalable and effective solution for AI generated speech detection. This research advances audio forensics and supports practical applications in media verification, voice authentication, and legal investigations.
