TY  - CONF
TI  - CNN-Driven Adaptive Encryption Framework for Securing Surveillance Videos Against Evolving Threats
AU  - Nayak, Lalita
AU  - Ambhaikar, Asha
AB  - This This paper proposes a novel Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN)-based adaptive encryption framework to secure surveillance videos, addressing the rising challenges posed by dynamic security threats such as frame tampering, synthetic content injection, and unauthorized access. The framework integrates CNNs to classify video content into risk categories (normal, sensitive, high-risk), and dynamically adjusts encryption schemes based on these classifications. Lowrisk frames are encrypted using lightweight AES-128 encryption, while high-risk frames are protected with robust RSA encryption, ensuring computational efficiency without compromising security. A frame-linked key management system is also implemented, providing strong, non-predictable keys for each session. The system is evaluated on several datasets, including the VIRAT Aerial Video Dataset and UCSD Anomaly Dataset, demonstrating high performance in terms of encryption/decryption time, classification accuracy, and resistance to various attacks. The proposed framework achieves a high level of adaptability, with significant improvements over conventional encryption methods in realtime surveillance video protection.
