TI  - Leveraging 3D CNNs for Robust Detection of GAN-Generated Medical Image Forgeries
AU  - L S, Sandhya
AU  - Ramanujan, Ajeesh
AB  - Medical images play a pivotal role in today’s health sector. With the advancement of technologies, clinical images from imaging devices are communicated to doctors or radiologists in real time via the Internet. However, this makes clinical images susceptible to tampering attacks. With the emergence of adversarial network architectures, generating deepfake content has become facile. Malicious actors may manipulate medical images to make false insurance claims, provide incorrect diagnoses, or even endanger someone’s life. Adversarial network poses a serious threat as they blur the line between authentic and manipulated images, making it difficult for doctors to discern the real from the fake. This paper proposes an efficient a nd robust 3D CNN model that helps the healthcare sector to distinguish real and tampered medical images. The proposed architecture performed well with a remarkable accuracy of \mathbf9 2. 7 7 %, \mathbf9 3. 7 8 % precision, and 92.60 % F1 score. Furthermore, this 3D CNN model performs well when compared to the existing model. This study reveals that tampering with medical images using adversarial networks can be detected utilizing 3DCNNs.
