TI  - Adaptive DCGAN and VGG16-based transfer learning for effective deepfake detection
AU  - Javiya, Deepa
AU  - Jethava, Gordhan
AU  - Parmar, Himani
AB  - Digital content generation technology evolved quickly which established deepfakes as a significant technological discovery. The manipulation capabilities of visual content by deepfakes create substantial threats for both digital security systems and information sharing integrity which occurs on social platforms. The developed deepfake detection framework unites a VGG16-based transfer learning model with an adaptive variant of DCGAN. The system benefitting from pretrained network characteristic extraction capabilities detect synthetic content efficiently with precision. A combination of optimized DCGAN architecture with VGG16 model pre-updating results in a system that reaches 97% accurate results within 50 epochs which decreases detection time compared to Lite-CNN solutions. The model exhibits elevated detection performance through extensive testing that validates both its accuracy and speed rate in operations. Secure content verification systems experience advancement through this research as it resolves the present digital market's requirement for effective real-time detection solutions against deepfakes.
