TI  - Pothole Detection using Deep Learning
AU  - Rao Alleshwaram, Venu Gopal
AU  - Kumar C, Sandeep
AU  - Reddy P, Chenna Kesava
AU  - Butchi Raju, K.
AU  - Anitha, Vulugundam
AU  - Rao, A. Veema
AB  - Road infrastructure plays a crucial role in ensuring connectivity, economic development, and public safety. However, the presence of potholes remains a major challenge, leading to vehicle damage, accidents, and costly repairs. Traditional methods of road inspection are labor-intensive and time-consuming, highlighting the need for automation. This proposed work presents a deep learning-based pothole detection system using the ResNet50 model, a powerful Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) known for its accuracy in image classification tasks. By employing transfer learning and preprocessing techniques, the model is trained to distinguish between damaged and undamaged road surfaces. We built an automated pothole-detection pipeline around a ResNet-50 backbone fine-tuned with transfer learning. The model processes road frames at 224 × 224 pixels, learns discriminative edge and texture cues, and labels each image as "damaged" or "sound." A balanced set of pothole and plain-road photos from open repositories fed the training loop. On held-out images the system kept accuracy above ninety percent and delivered high precision, which limits false alarms on smooth asphalt. A lightweight Flask dashboard renders the predictions instantly and can run from a dashboard camera or curb-side node. This outcome shows that deep networks can flag defects in real time, giving maintenance teams clear, location-tagged alerts while cutting inspection labor. The system not only enhances the efficiency of road monitoring but also contributes to the development of safer and smarter transportation infrastructure. This AI-powered approach can significantly reduce manual inspection efforts and aid municipal authorities in timely maintenance and repair.
