TY  - CONF
TI  - ForensicAI-Net: An Ensemble Model Framework for Strengthening Forensic Science in India's Criminal Justice System
AU  - U, Ragavee
AU  - Sriraghavan, K.
AU  - Rajan, M.
AU  - Raghul, R.
AU  - Sudharshan, S.
AU  - Sathiyaselvam, S.A.
AB  - Forensic science is very important whenever investigating a crime, and the development of artificial intelligence (AI) has enhanced the process of analyzing forensic evidence. ResNet-152, Capsule Networks, Transformer-ViT, Graph Neural Networks are ensemble models used to create an ensemble model framework known as ForensicAI-Net, which improves forensic science in the Indian criminal justice system. The model was tested on several types of forensic data, such as fingerprints, image data at the crime scene, biometric scans, legal documents, and crime network data. With the ResNet-152-powered forensic image recognition module, the accuracy of the system in identifying fingerprints and classifying ballistic evidence was 96.8% and 94.2% respectively. BERT-RoBERTa model showed accuracy of 94.5% in detecting tampering in forensic documents and Capsule Networks showed high accuracy of 92.1% in detecting forging of handwriting. The biometric analysis model, based on Transformer-ViT, recorded 97.8% on facial recognition, and the Siamese Networks recorded 94.6% on the matching of latent fingerprints. Crime pattern detection models based on Graph Neural Networks predicted criminal networks with an accuracy of 95.6% and crime prediction models based on reinforcement learning proposed an accuracy of 93.2%. The suggested framework can make a great contribution to forensic decision-making, the efficiency of crime investigation, and the validation of legal evidence. Future directions will be in real-time deployment of forensic AI, federated learning to perform privacy-preserving forensic analysis, and improvement of interpretability to enforce legal compliance.
