TY  - CONF
TI  - A Comparative Analysis of Custom CNN, Inception-V3, MobileNet, RestNet-50, and VGG-19 in Detecting AI-Generated Images
AU  - Putra, Verindra Hernanda
AU  - Sailendra, Zahra Amiera Putri
AU  - Hartakaadi, Marcelia Chintya
AU  - Pratama, Rafi Andhika Putra
AU  - Corputty, Felix
AB  - This research addresses the issue of image classification using convolutional neural networks (CNN) with the objective of distinguishing AI-generated images from real images. This is a significant challenge in fields like digital forensics and media verification due to the realism of synthetic images. This study compares five CNN architectures: Inception-V3, ResNet-50, VGG-19, MobileNet, and a custom model, MBC-Net, which was developed to evaluate whether a simpler model can compete with well-established architectures. A balanced dataset of 20,000 images was constructed, consisting of 10,000 real and 10,000 AI-generated images spanning ten human and animal categories. The evaluation was conducted on the test set using accuracy, precision, and recall, under various learning rate and optimizer settings. The results show that Inception-V3 achieves the highest detection accuracy, reaching 0.984, while MobileNet demonstrated consistent stability across all test scenarios. MBC-Net also showed competitive performance, outperforming some pretrained models in certain cases. While model architecture is the primary factor for peak performance, the findings confirm that hyperparameter tuning is also critical. Although Inception-V3 offers high accuracy, its computational cost limits deployment in real-time systems. These findings provide practical insights that can help developers choose suitable models for building applications that detect AI-generated content under real-world constraints.
